<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1849-09-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1849-09-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="209" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d209">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Clayton</persName>,
                                    Secretary of State, to Mr. <persName type="to">Hall</persName>,
                                    district attorney</hi>.</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Confidential.—Telegram.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <dateline><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of
                                        State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1849-09-07"><hi rend="italic">September</hi> 7,
                                    1849</date>.</dateline>
                            <p rend="flushleft"><hi rend="smallcaps">J. Prescott Hall</hi>,
                                    Esq.,<lb/><hi rend="italic">United States District Attorney, New
                                    York:</hi></p>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Act according to your own discretion
                                in the case of * * *; and the vessels also. Break up the
                                enterprise—that is the great object. If <pb facs="0700" n="686" xml:id="pg_686"/> the Government had no other motive, it is
                                all-important to save the lives of the ignorant dupes of the
                                project. Their fate in Cuba would be most disastrous. No vindictive
                                proceedings are desirable, in my judgment, after the enterprise is
                                broken up. * * *</p>
                            <p>Very respectfully, yours,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>J. M. CLAYTON.</signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>